<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Student Law Think Tank, Northumbria University (CRJ 04)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence from the Student Law Think Tank, Northumbria University (CRJ 04)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Foreword</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This document is a response to the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee’s consultation about the role of the judiciary if there were a codified constitution.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> It was produced by Northumbria University’s Student Law Think Tank, which is a School of Law student society. The aim of the Student Law Think Tank is to involve students with policy work and get students’ voices heard across society. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Aims</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The aim of this document was for Northumbria University School of Law students to take up the invitation to contribute to the debate about the role of the judiciary if there were a codified constitution.  Whilst some staff </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> involved in helping the proj</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ect come to fruition the content of the response is entirely the work of the students.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This Student Law Think Tank decided to focus upon question 3 of the consultation:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">If the UK were to have a codified constitution, what powers should the courts have </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if they held that a piece of legislation was unconstitutional?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What would be the implications of these powers on existing constitutional doctrines, including parliamentary sovereignty and judicial review?</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">b)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In the context of question 3, what can we</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> learn from the interaction between the UK courts and the European Court of Justice and European Court of Human Rights?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Approach</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The comments below were collected over a series of large group meetings over the course of three weeks in which the contents of the response were questioned and debated.  This document is the work of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">22 students.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  It takes into account the opinions of all </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of the contributors to the response, and although it has been edited and reformatted, it aims to record both the areas of consensus which were reached as well as reflecting the areas where divergence of opinion emerged. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Chapter 1: Summary of Evidence </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">The following are the conclusions of the Student Law Think Tank:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">The Courts should have the two key powers to declare legislation invalid or incompatible allowing for challenge before and after implementation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">That the senior Courts (specifically High </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Court and above) would be able to exercise the two powers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">A separate constitutional court was not favoured.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">That the decisions made in relation to the constitutional validity or compatibility of a piece of legislation would be done by a super majority dec</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">ision and that only single judgments would be given for clarity. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">v)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">That there would be an effect on existing constitutional doctrines such as parliamentary supremacy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">vi)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">There were distinct advantages from copying and learning from the approaches adopted by th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">e European Court of Justice and the European Court of Human Rights in dealing with and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">managing constitutional issues.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> </span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Chapter </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">: Response to question 3 </span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">When deciding what powers the Courts should have if they held that a piece of legislation was </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">unconstitutional, stud</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ents of Northumbria University </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">focussed primarily upon two different types of powers:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Declaration of invalidity;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Declaration of incompatibility. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">These powers were identified as being the actual powers the Courts should possess when </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">dealing with unconstitutional legislation. Below these two powers are discussed on their merits:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of invalidity:</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  This is the Courts’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> ultimate power in terms of opposing legislation that it deemed to be unconstitutional. A declaration of invali</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ity would represent the Court’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> view that the legislation is for any reason totally incompatible with the UK constitution and that it should therefore be struck down immediately by way of the Court’s judgment. This power echoes the power of the US Supreme </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Court in declaring law unconstitutional. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of Incompatibility: </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This is a lesser power, but may be preferable in the bulk of instances. A declaration of incompatibility would be used when the Courts rule that legislation, if enacted (or once enac</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ted), would be incompatible with the UK constitution. The Courts could use this power to inform Parliament that a statute should be rectified to ensure that it compatibility with the constitution. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Although it was debated whether or not the Courts should p</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ossess either or both of these powers, it was widely considered that these would be the key powers of a judiciary equipped to deal with a written and codified constitution. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Think Tank then moved to discuss when and how the Courts would employ these p</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">owers and as such a number of key questions were raised: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">When Would The Above Powers Be Used? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Discussion centred around two main questions with regards to when the Court would be entitled to exercise the above powers:</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Should the Courts be allowed to ad</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">vise parliament on the constitutional validity of legislation prior to its implementation? Or, alternatively;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Should the Courts be limited to assess the constitutional validity of legislation only after its implementation, on a case-by-case “challenge” bas</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">is?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Clearly each approach has advantages and disadvantages of how they would operate in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">practice,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> however at this point during the discussion a vote was taken by members on which approach was favoured. This vote was taken under the assumption that Courts </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be awarded both the power to declare legislation invalid, and the lesser power of declaring law incompatible with the constitution.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> It was favoured by members that a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">llowing the Courts to use the powers </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">before and after</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> implementation of</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the legislati</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">on. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was decided that the Courts should be allowed to challenge the law prior to implementation, for example by stating during the House of Lords stage, that it is foreseeable that the law could be unconstitutional if raised as part of a claim. Allowin</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">g the judiciary to raise any foreseeable issues to Parliament prior to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">implementation benefits the procedure as a whole as it seeks to maintain clarity in the law. Also the obvious benefit to this approach is that it seeks to prevent challenges in Courts r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">esulting from the proposed law after it has been enacted. If the judiciary are able to comment on the law prior to its implementation then it allows both law makers and the judiciary to exchange views and expertise, which in theory should lead to better qu</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ality legislation. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was largely agreed that it was essential that the Courts be able to rule legislation either invalid or incompatible with the constitution in conjunction with judgments on an ad-hoc basis. If the Courts were allowed to exercise this </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">power in regard to declaring a law invalid, then it was decided that the best route for the judiciary would be that the Court could send the law back to Parliament with notes on its concerns over its constitutionality. It was suggested that the Court</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> shoul</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> have the power to impose a time limit on parliament in such an instance, during which time the legislation would, in effect, be temporarily invalid. This method was favoured as a principal power for the Courts, in contrast with allowing the Courts to str</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ike down l</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">egislation</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> outright. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Which Courts/Judges should have the powers to declare legislation incompatible/invalid?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This question resulted from the above discussion. If UK Courts are afforded these powers, which Courts specifically?</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Which Court would </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">have the power to decide on the constitutionality of legislation and how would this process take place?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">How would the Courts implement these powers? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">With regard to the first question above, the following issues were addressed by members:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Firstly, which Co</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">urt(s) would be afforded the powers to decide on constitutional issues? Discussion mainly focused around the issue of whether a separate Constitutional Court would be required or whether the current Court structure would be able to deal with constitutional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> issues. Members took time to examine the hierarchy of Courts in other jurisdictions which include Constitutional Courts such as </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Ireland and South Africa, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">however a majority of members were in favour of affording powers to only the Senior Courts (High C</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ourt and above). One issue raised against this notion was whether the Courts would be able to cope with any increase in caseload brought on by constitutional law actions. Another issue raised was that of established appeal routes and how these would be aff</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ected by the introduction of a Constitutional Court. With members initially against the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">introduction of a separate Constitutional Court it was decided that actions on constitutional matters should be issued initially in the High Court. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The introduction o</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">f a Constitutional Court was not ruled out by members however. It was unanimously agreed that any such Court would have to sit at the same level as the UK Supreme Court in terms of hierarchy, given the powers it would possess. The main points of discussion</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> on the necessity for a Constitutional Court were as follows:</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">How the decision would be made as to what was a Supreme Court issue and what was a Constitutional Court issue?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Would the Constitutional Court be able to change or challenge its own decisions? </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ould there be any route of appeal from the Constitutional Court? </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Practical issue of case load and appointing judges</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Where would the ECJ fit into this equation? </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Would a single judgment be favoured over individual judgments?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A lot of discussion centred on</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> what type of judgment should be given by the Court in relation to constitutional issues. The types of judgments discussed ranged from a simple majority or whether a super majority</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">would be favoured,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for example</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> mirroring that of the criminal jury system. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Again, members thought it best to take a vote to decide which approach is favoured. Due to the inherent importance of constitutional issues, it was held by the majority that a super majority of judgments was the preferred method. Continuity and clarity in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">the constitution would also be positive aspects of this method.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The next discussion point was, in a Constitutional Court, how many judges would sit as a panel. Again, by majority, it was held that a panel should mimic that of the Supreme Court; therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a panel ranging between 5-9 judges should sit depending upon the importance of the constitutional issue.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Finally, members debated the type of majority req</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">uired in a panel judgment when</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the Court has the power to make declarations on the constitutionality </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">of legislation. This issue was hotly debated wi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">th many members having different</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> views. Those in fav</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">our of publishing all the judge</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> decisions and judgments believed that it was crucial for the public to be able to read obiter statements and reasoning behi</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nd the decisions. However, it was marginally decided that due to the nature of the constitution as entrenched law, single judgments would be more appropriate as it would maintain the clarity in the law and allow the law to be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">understandable and more easily</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> applicable in other cases that come before the Courts. It was thought that publishing dissenting judgments in constitutional cases would lead to an increase in actions and appeals.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Following this discussion, the majority of members remained unconvinced t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">hat a written and codified UK constitution would necessitate the introduction of a separate Constitutional Court, although the introduction of a separate constitutional division of the High Court was favoured.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Chapter </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">: Response to question 3a  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Members predominantly looked at four key constitutional doctrines </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">they</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> felt could be affected by the granting of powers to the Courts: </span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Parliamentary Supremacy </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Rule of Law</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Separation of Powers </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Judicial Review</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Parliamentary Supremacy:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘The principle o</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">f Parliamentary sovereignty mean neither more nor less than this, namely that Parliament thus defined has, under the English constitution, the right to make or unmake any law whatever: and, further, that no person or body is recognised by the law of Englan</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d as having a right to override or set aside the legislation of Parliament.’ —</span><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Dicey"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A.V. Dicey</span></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Introduction to the Study of the Law of the Constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(1885)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The conclusion reached in </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">relation to parliamentary supremacy was that </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">if the powers discussed above were granted to the C</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ourts that the doctrine of supremacy would be </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">adversely impacted</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. The main concern in this area was that the power of the Courts to challenge laws created by </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rliament would impact upon the traditional doctrine that it is f</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ree to create any law it wishes, and that the Courts cannot challenge a parliamentary enactment.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  It was felt that the impact upon the doctrine would depend heavily upon the exact powers given</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> to the Courts to challenge the unconstitutional piece of legislation. If the Courts had the power to effectively declare a piece of legislation completely invalid as discussed above then it was concluded that the impact of this power upon the doctrine wou</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ld be quite significant as it would effectively allow the Court to curtail the powers of Parliament in creating laws. It was felt that if the Courts were given the power to simply declare a piece of legislation incompatible and required Parliament to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">chang</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e the unconstitutional piece of law to be compatible with the constitution then this would have less of a direct effect on the doctrine itself. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was felt that there was a more fundamental problem in relation </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to parliamentary supremacy beyond</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the impact</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> any powers granted to the Courts under a codified constitution would have. The main point raised and set out here was that the creation of a codified constitution itself would have a direct impact upon the doctrine as it is difficult to see how the doctri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ne would continue to exist and be justified when Parliament would be forced to ensure that any laws created by itself fell in line with the constitution which would need to be entrenched to ensure its continued effectiveness and operation. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A new constituti</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">onal settlement would be required, setting out the powers of each of the three branches of the state. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The Rule of Law:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was felt and concluded by members that set powers for the Courts in relation to protecting the constitution would help to reinforce the doctrine of the rule of law in that it would more clearly set out the powers of the Courts. One issue that was forese</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">en in relation to this doctrine was the status of the constitution in terms of what Dicey referred to as ‘ordinary law’. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If there was a codified constitution this would remove the issue of ‘ordinary law’ by creating a hierarchy of laws stemming from the co</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">nstitution. This would enforce Lord Bingham’s view that law </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">must be accessible and so far as possible intelligible, clear and predictable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Separation of Powers:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Again it was felt that any further powers given to the Courts to challenge any unconstitutional</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> legislation would help to further protect the doctrine of the separation of powers. In conclusion it was decided that any further clarification of the powers of the legislature, government and the judiciary helped to further the doctrine and ensure that t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he power</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s possessed by the 3 branches w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ere set out more clearly and effectively. Furthermore it was noted by members that affording more power to the judiciary may </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">result in a better</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> balance to a system of checks and balances which is heavily weighted towa</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rds the legislature </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">and the executive currently. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Judicial </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">R</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">eview:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">In relation to judicial review it was concluded that the doctrine would not be seriously affected by any powers given to the Courts in relation to challenging unconstitutional legislation. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was felt that there should be no reason why the powers of the Court in relation to a codified constitution should not allow Courts </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to deal with unconstitutional decision making processes of public bodies, hence further increasing the power of the doctri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ne of judicial review. It was mooted that the power to challenge the actual decision rather than the decision making process as is currently the case under judicial review could simply be the next organic evolution of the doctrine, especially when one cons</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">iders the European </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Court of Human Rights’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> approach of increasing judicial scrutiny of public bodies.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Article 13 ECHR</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> requires that n</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ational legal systems must provide an effective remedy for breach of Convention rights</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> in that the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">European Court </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">has found </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">(several times) that judicial review </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">may not be an effective remedy because cannot investigate merits</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. As such it was felt that a new basis for judicial review could be created similar to the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">incompatibility with convention rights</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> basis by having an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> incomp</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">atibility with the constitution</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> basis. </span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Chapter </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">: Response to question 3b</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The m</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">embers </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">discussed numerous reference points in this area</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> single judgments</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">from the European institutions. The following were discussed</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> the most:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-23.31pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">i.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If a</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Constitutional Court</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> was</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> introduced to the UK, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">specialist chambers be formed within it to assure judgments remained clear and properly informed?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-26.37pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">ii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">If, like in the USA, it was made very difficult to alter the constitution itself, how would the UK cope</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> with European directives etc</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and associated timelines?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It was noted that now might be the best time to codify the UK constitution, given the amount of guidance we have already gained from the European institutions, both on EU law and the law of human ri</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">ghts. Some members felt that codifying the UK constitution and entrenching it would create the potential for conflict with the European institutions in situations where the UK constitution was itself incompatible with the European Convention on Human Right</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">s or EU Law. By definition the content of the constitution would be much more difficult to change than traditional statute law. One suggestion for preventing such problems was to include a system of fast-tracking the concerns of the EU and the Convention w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">hereby changes to the UK constitution necessary to comply with the European institutions could be made much more quickly.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">All other EU countries and members of the Council of Europe have written constitutions and as such there could be much to learn from t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">heir approaches on this issue. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">31 October 2013</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Appendix: Contributors</span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Staff Support</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Claire McCann</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Christopher Rogers</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written By</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Jack McDonald (Board Member)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Tom Duggan (Shadow Board Member)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; fon